Taylor, the powerful figure behind civil wars in Liberia and Sierra Leone, faces war crimes charges.
His family claims lack of time and resources for his defense, accusing the court of privacy violations.
The trial, moved to The Hague, has faced delays due to defense preparation issues.
Prosecutors argue the defense has adequate resources, but Taylor's lawyers struggle to gather witnesses.
Despite funding challenges, the trial is set to begin in June.
Witnesses fear UN travel bans if they testify for Taylor.
The trial aims for a fair process amid complexities and security concerns.
